## Tool 4: list_indexes

**Definition:** Returns all indexes defined on a collection. Indexes are the most important
performance signal in MongoDB. Every index tells you two things: which field is queried frequently
enough to warrant an index, and what annotation belongs on that field in your Java entity.
Missing an index annotation means Spring Data won’t create it (if auto-index-creation is true)
or your code is out of sync with the DB (if auto-index-creation is false).

**Parameters:**

```json
{
  "database": "your_db_name",
  "collection": "collection_name"
}
```

**Example:**

```
Input:  list_indexes({ "database": "bnp_trade_db", "collection": "orders" })

Output:
  [
    { "name": "_id_",           "key": { "_id": 1 } },
    { "name": "user_id_1",      "key": { "user_id": 1 } },
    { "name": "email_unique",   "key": { "email": 1 },  "unique": true },
    { "name": "status_date_idx","key": { "order_status": 1, "created_at": -1 } },
    { "name": "desc_text",      "key": { "description": "text" } },
    { "name": "expires_ttl",    "key": { "expires_at": 1 }, "expireAfterSeconds": 86400 }
  ]
```

**Decode each index into Java:**

```
_id_                                →  No annotation needed (automatic)

user_id_1 (single, not unique)      →  @Indexed
                                       @Field("user_id") private String userId;

email_unique (unique: true)         →  @Indexed(unique = true)
                                       private String email;

status_date_idx (compound)          →  At CLASS level:
                                       @CompoundIndex(
                                         name = "status_date_idx",
                                         def = "{'order_status':1, 'created_at':-1}"
                                       )

desc_text (text index)              →  @TextIndexed
                                       private String description;

expires_ttl (TTL, expireAfterSeconds)→  @Indexed(expireAfterSeconds = 86400)
                                        @Field("expires_at") private LocalDateTime expiresAt;
```

**What goes wrong without this:** Your Java entity has no `@Indexed` on `userId`. If
auto-index-creation is true, Spring doesn’t create the index. Every query by userId performs
a COLLSCAN (full collection scan) — on 45,000 documents this takes 2–3 seconds instead of 5ms.

