## Tool 7: insert_one

**Definition:** Inserts a single document into a collection. Use ONLY when the user explicitly
asks to create test data or seed a document. Never call during schema analysis.

**Parameters:**

```json
{
  "database": "your_db_name",
  "collection": "collection_name",
  "document": { "field": "value" }
}
```

**Safety rule:** Always show the document to the user before inserting. Confirm the collection name.

-----

## Tool 8: update_one / update_many

**Definition:** `update_one` modifies the first document matching a filter. `update_many` modifies
all matching documents. These are destructive — they change live data.

**Parameters:**

```json
{
  "database": "your_db_name",
  "collection": "collection_name",
  "filter": { "order_status": "PENDING" },
  "update": { "$set": { "order_status": "CANCELLED" } }
}
```

**Safety rule:** Always show the filter and the update operation to the user and wait for explicit
confirmation before calling. Run count_documents with the same filter first to show how many
documents will be affected.

-----

## Tool 9: delete_one / delete_many

**Definition:** `delete_one` permanently removes the first matching document. `delete_many`
removes all matching documents. These are irreversible.

**Safety rule:** NEVER call without explicit written confirmation from the user. Before asking,
run count_documents with the same filter and show the user exactly how many documents will be
deleted. State that this cannot be undone.

-----

## Tool 10: create_index

**Definition:** Creates a new index on a collection directly in the running MongoDB instance.
Use this when recommending performance improvements alongside the code changes — create the index
in the DB and add the annotation in Java at the same time so they stay in sync.

**Parameters:**

```json
{
  "database": "your_db_name",
  "collection": "collection_name",
  "keys": { "user_id": 1, "created_at": -1 },
  "options": { "name": "user_created_idx", "unique": false }
}
```

**Index direction:** `1` = ascending, `-1` = descending. Match direction to the most common
sort direction — a query that sorts `created_at DESC` benefits from a `-1` index.

